s as <i>Bulenemera</i>, is from <i>bulena</i> (genitive plural of <i>bula</i>) + <i>mere</i> ‘lake’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bowmer","meanings":["English (Derbyshire): variant of   Bulmer  .","Americanized form of German   Baumer  ."]},{"name":"Bolmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Bulmer  .","Dutch: probably from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldemar</i>, composed of the elements <i>bald</i> ‘bold’ + <i>mar</i> ‘famous’."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Emma de Bulmer was born in 1154, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with Geoffrey de Neville. She died in 1208, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1154–1208":"1154–1208","1145–1193":"1145–1193","1176–1254":"1176–1254","29 September 1193":"29. september 1193","1145":"1145","1254":"1254","1154":"1154","1176":"1176","1193":"1193","1208":"1208","Brancepeth, Durham, England":"Brancepeth, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England":"Horncastle, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1154–1208":"1154–1208","1145–1193":"1145–1193","1176–1254":"1176–1254","29 September 1193":"29. syyskuuta 1193","1145":"1145","1254":"1254","1154":"1154","1176":"1176","1193":"1193","1208":"1208","Brancepeth, Durham, England":"Brancepeth, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","